 how this plays out in the daily practices and experiences of those who continue to reside in segregated communities needs to be articulated and understood before Belfast can truly claim its ‘post-conflict’ status.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSegregationxNorthern IrelandxBelfastxNorthern IrelandxBelfast. 0aSegregationzNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 0aTeenagersxSocial conditionsxNorthern IrelandxBelfast. 0aTeenagerszNorthern IrelandzBelfastxAttitudes. 0aTeenagerszNorthern IrelandzBelfastxSocial conditions. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aCatholics.  aProtestants.  aarchitecture.  aintractable conflict.  anorthern Ireland.  apeace walls.  aphysical divisions.  apost-conflict Belfast.  asocial relations.  asocial relationships.  asymbolic divisions.  ateenagers' perceptions.1 aLeonard, Madeleine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612043440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526120434423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526120434/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles